[1]
Date: Fri, 6 Dec 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and New Vision (Kampala) (edited)
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200212090137.html>

Cholera Outbreak Strikes Kampala City
-------------------------------------
The Kampala City Council (KCC) yesterday issued a cholera alert. One
person has died of suspected cholera and 7 suspects were admitted to
Mulago Hospital on Wed, 4 Dec 2002.
KCC officials said the outbreak was the first in the city since
1997/98. The Kampala District Health Services chief, Dr. Mishack
Mubiru, denied that 12 other suspects had been admitted to Mulago.
Initial reports said 12 people had been admitted and that a special
unit had been created in the hospital to handle the victims.
Mubiru said the dead person and the 7 suspects were from
Nateete-Kitaka zone in Rubaga Division. "We have alerted our staff
in all division health units and NGO hospitals to report any cases of
diarrhea. We are mobilizing the public on hygiene," Mubiru said.
The first case of suspected cholera in the area was reported on Sun,
1 Dec 2002. City officials attributed the outbreak to poor
sanitation. Mubiru said the cases were manageable and did not
necessitate a special unit. "At the moment, we don't need a special
unit, though with cholera cases you have to isolate the patients. If
the cases increase, we will move to the Mulago hospital football
field like in the 1997/98 outbreak, to avoid cross-infection," he
said.
He said the district had the ability to contain the outbreak but
advised the public and visitors to ensure proper hygiene and to boil
drinking water, avoid pre-packed water and juices sold in polythene
bags, use only tap water, and avoid water from spring wells until
further notice. He warned against eating food prepared in markets
and urged the public to call to report suspected cases of cholera.
[Byline: Steven Candia]
