Date: Mon, 9 Dec 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and New Vision (Kampala) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200212100079.html>

Cholera Likely At Gaba Landing Site
-----------------------------------
There is likely to be a cholera outbreak at Gaba landing site in
Makindye division, officials from the department of Public Health in
Kampala district have warned.
The poor disposal of garbage, stagnant water, and the selling of fish
and cooked food in a filthy environment at the site almost forced
Kampala City Council officials to close it recently. The place is
full of flies with the smell of fish drifting in the air.
The KCC officials were touring the landing site, which employs over
500 people. The officials included Francis Lubowa, the city
secretary for health, hygiene and environment protection. "The
situation is very bad. Hygiene is poor," Mubiru said.
******
[3]
Date: Mon, 9 Dec 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and New Vision (Kampala) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200212100154.html>

Cholera Spreads to Wakiso
-------------------------
Health officials yesterday said the cholera outbreak in the city had
reached worrying proportions with the disease spreading to Wakiso
district and claiming 2 more lives. This brings the death toll to 3.
The Kampala district director of health services, Dr. Mishack Mubiru,
on Sat, 7 Dec 2002, said the epidemic had also spread to Bugolobi, a
city suburb in Mutungo Parish, Nakawa division, bringing the
geographical spread of the epidemic in the city to 2 divisions.
On that day, a person from Banda in Nakawa division died of cholera
in Mulago Hospital while a resident of Nansana, Wakiso district, died
on Fri, 6 Dec 2002 night of the same disease in Mulago Hospital.
Health officials on Thur, 5 Dec 2002, said a child from Nateete
Central zone had died of cholera.
Mubiru announced that plans were underway to establish a cholera
treatment center in Mulago hospital to cater to the increasing number
of patients and to avoid cross-infection.
"We expect that this center will be fully functional by Tue, 10 Dec
2002. It will be isolated like we did in 1997/98. We cannot take
chances because other patients may get infected," Mubiru said. "So
far there have been 14 cumulative cases of victims admitted and
discharged."
Kampala Mayor John Ssebaana Kizito and district health officials
toured Kitaka zone in Rubaga division where the out break was first
reported.
[Byline: Steven Candia]
